<HEAD>Conference Urges Battle Against ``Greenhouse'' Effect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every car should yield 42 miles per gallon and carbon dioxide emissions should be cut 20 percent to fight the `` greenhouse effect'' that may threaten Earth's climate and human health, a conference recommended Friday. Four hundred scientists and public officials from 13 countries attended the four-day Global Climate Change meeting that focused on the warming of the atmosphere and damage to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s protective ozone layer. `` The activities of 5 billion people on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> are clearly producing changes in the world's climate,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Harwell </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s Global Environment Program. `` In our lifetimes, and certainly in our children's, climate changes and other environmental impacts will profoundly affect the way humans live.'' The participants called for changes in human activities whose by-products are gases that may be causing a rise in atmospheric temperatures, resulting in hotter summers, droughts, more violent storms, rising sea levels and an increase in diseases. The participants urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to pass a more stringent version of the Clean Air Act, and to stop production by the year 2000 of all chlorofluorocarbons, which cause the `` greenhouse'' effect. They also recommended that the fuel economy of all new cars be increased by 1 -LCB- mpg per year to at least 42 mpg by the year 2000. Other energy sources, including nuclear plants, should be used more efficiently and with added safety standards, the participants said. The conference also urged that land use and building controls be enacted to provide for nature conservation, coupled with increased mass transit that would reduce automobile congestion. The conference was convened by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, Gov. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Keane </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, Gov. <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Among those who addressed the meeting were physicist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagan </PERSON>; <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> cable network; Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, Jr., D-Tenn.; and Sen. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>, D-Colo The 150 scientists attending the meeting included <PERSON> Vassily </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokolov </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Ma </PERSON> <PERSON> Shijun </PERSON>, chairman of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the Environment. `` We must learn to understand and live rather than fight natural forces, including those unleashed by our own activities,'' said the participants in their final recommendation.
