<HEAD>Judge: Mother Linked To Daughter's Suicide Can Get Profits From Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead and 2nd graf; SUBS 7th graf, `Lawyers said...',
to DELETE incorrect reference to first use of ``psychological autopsy.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman convicted of instigating her daughter's suicide by pushing her to work as a nude dancer will be allowed to profit from her story, a judge has ruled. `` I'm very happy,'' <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Thursday. `` I'm glad to get it over with.'' The agreement between the state and Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, approved Thursday by <ORGANIZATION> Broward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franza </PERSON>, will require her to share whatever money she might get from her story with the state and with her 18-year-old son. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Draves </PERSON>, estimated her client could receive between $ 50,000 to $ 200,000 for film and book rights to her story. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 42, was convicted in October 1987 of child abuse, forgery and procuring a sexual performance by a child. She was sentenced to a year in jail but is free on bail during an appeal. Her 17-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancini </PERSON>, shot and killed herself in the family's <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> home in March 1986. During a two-week trial, state prosecutors claimed Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> traumatized her daughter by encouraging her to work as a nude dancer, even forging the girl's birth certificate to make it appear she was older. Lawyers said the case was the first in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in which a person was charged with mental child abuse in connection with a suicide. Originally, the state had sought to block Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> from getting any money, citing a never-before-used state law barring felons from profiting from depictions of their crimes. Under terms of Thursday's settlement, the state would receive about $ 35,000 for trial and jail costs from any earnings Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> receives from her story. Part of the remaining earnings would be shared by Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 18-year-old son. Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s former attorney, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitman </PERSON>, has his own claim pending against Ms. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, contending he is owed $ 150,000 in attorney's fees from the trial, and he is seeking to overturn the agreement with the state. A hearing on that claim is scheduled for next week.
