<HEAD>Amnesia Victim Tries to Piece Together His Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About the only clue the stocky, balding middle-aged man has about his past is the name `` <PERSON> Snuffy </PERSON>'' engraved on the back of his belt. He does n't know who he is, how he got to <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION> or anything before Feb. 8, when he awoke in a wooded area near <LOCATION> Shands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> with no wallet and no form of identification. He is 5-foot-11, weighs 250 pounds and has a tattoo on his arm. He was wearing blue jeans, boots, flannel shirt and tinted prescription glasses when found. The hospital said brain scans and other evaluations showed no signs of a blow to the head or any other physical causes for amnesia, such as epilepsy or alcohol-related brain malfunction. Dr. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Shands </ORGANIZATION> psychiatrist, said the man is apparently suffering from a psychological form of amnesia, probably triggered by a great mental shock or stress. The man fears family members may be worrying about him somewhere. `` It took two or three days to sort of pull myself through the fog,'' the man said. `` I spend every waking moment trying to figure out who ... I am.'' The man, who is fairly articulate, speaks with a Southwestern accent and likes to read, sat with mental health counselor W.J. <PERSON> Tootie </PERSON> <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> and posed for pictures Thursday in hopes of a breakthrough _ someone who remembers what he ca n't. He said the name `` Snuffy'' does n't ring a bell for him. `` I did n't like it at first,'' he said, but `` it seems better than <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>.'' Ms. <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> said her client is able to talk and interact with people well. He has been reading voraciously, especially newspapers. The <LOCATION> Alachua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's office has taken the man's fingerprints and physical description; there are apparently no warrants for his arrest There is a good chance that his memory will return, either in bits and pieces or a sudden rush, authorities said. Most similar amnesia victims regain most or all their memory within a few days or weeks. <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON> said forgetting an entire life is especially rare. The chances are `` you're going to find that there's something that this guy's getting away from,'' <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON> said. `` Whatever I'm responsible for, I want to live up to,'' said the mystery man.
