<HEAD>Tower Backers Want Him to Testify Before Full Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> allies, struggling to gain the offensive in a tense confirmation battle, are suggesting that the defense secretary-designate come to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor and respond `` charge by charge'' to the allegations against him. `` If we owe Senator Tower anything, we owe him the right to say, ` I've had my day in court,''' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> GOP Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said Friday as <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>'s confirmation chances dimmed further with two additional Democrats joining the opposition. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> stopped short of turning his suggestion into a formal proposal, and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said he would be `` happy to consider any request.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> also said he was troubled by the confirmation proceedings, in which material from a confidential <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report that is damaging to Tower has been leaked in the news media but may not be discussed openly on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. He became the second senior Democrat in as many days to suggest a closed <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> session to permit a full airing of the allegations contained in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report. Tower has been battling questions of his drinking habits, his behavior toward women and his lucrative work as a defense industry consultant after serving as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms control negotiator. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report contains numerous allegations, but Republicans say few if any of them are corroborated, and insist nothing in it disqualifies him from the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is in recess until Monday, when debate is expected to resume on the nomination, although Tower and several senators are certain to keep the controversy alive over the weekend with appearances scheduled on television interview programs. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> vote count shows 47 Democrats and GOP Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON> either committed or leaning against the nomination and 40 Republicans committed or leaning in favor, with the rest undecided. The Democrats hold a 55-45 majority in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s surprise suggestion _ only six people have ever been called to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 200 years to answer charges against them _ came near the end of a day of debate in which two additional Democrats announced their opposition and a string of Republicans complained that Tower was being treated unfairly. `` We've got to even up the score somehow,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> GOP leader. Arguing that limitations on public references to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report make it impossible `` to get at the truth,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> suggested bringing Tower to the floor `` to answer his critics face-to-face, charge-by-charge, rumor-by-rumor and fact-by-fact.'' Several Republicans defended Tower earlier in a long day of debate. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has abandoned fairness and the object of that abandonment is <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said the evidence in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report was so flimsy that no prosecutor would use it for an indictment, and said of Tower, `` He is my friend. I thought he was your friend and I want some justice for my friend.'' Sen. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, R-Idaho. called on a few Democrats to swing behind the nomination before partisanship overwhelmed the debate completely, but the only two Democrats to announce _ conservative <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and liberal <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> _ said they would oppose confirmation. <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> had been counted by the White House as a potential convert to Tower's cause, but in a written statement, he noted the allegations against Tower and said, `` We can not take a chance. An angry Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, called for the release of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report, noting the Republican charge that the Democrats have based their opposition on allegations, not facts. `` It's our character that's being assassinated here and I'm sick and tired of it,'' said <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>. Release of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report is a decision that only the White House can make.
