<DATELINE>PENSACOLA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Merchants and town officials in this barrier island resort community have hatched an idea they think will put them in the pink. With nary a squawk Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rosa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> endorsed a plan to turn <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>'s water tower into a 10-story pink flamingo <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Garmon </PERSON>, sales manager for <ORGANIZATION> Lamar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a billboard company in nearby <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, pitched the idea, dubbed `` Project Pink,'' to the panel. He said the big bird could be to <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> what the Eiffel Tower is to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and the Statue of Liberty is to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He even envisioned an entry in the Guinness Book of World Records. Several merchants urged approval. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Orenstein </PERSON>, general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cottage </ORGANIZATION>, said shops could sell pink flamingo T-shirts, bars could serve similarly themed drinks and the community could have a pink flamingo parade. Cost of construction the bird could be borne by business sponsors, the merchants suggested. The proposal goes to the authority's full board next week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pigeons ignored plastic owls, traps and helium balloons; they were unruffled by high-frequency sound waves. So authorities are now mulling using a sticky paste to dissuade the birds from roosting at hangers at an airpark. Pigeon droppings have destroyed insulation in the new $ 40 million hangars at <ORGANIZATION> Chennault </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airpark </ORGANIZATION> and corroded paint on the KC-135 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> tankers refurbished at the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant, officials say. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> is considered a bird sanctuary, and a city ordinance forbids hunting, trapping and shooting birds within city limits. At a public hearing to address the problem Thursday, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> said his company makes an adhesive that's strong enough to alarm the pigeons _ and make them stay away from places they've encountered it _ but too weak to make the birds permanent fixtures. The repellant, a clear, sticky gel, is guaranteed for two years, is non-toxic and does not sting, burn or harm birds, said <PERSON> Avery </PERSON>, of Hot Foot International in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>.
