<HEAD>Developments in Eastern Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with strike called; no pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a summary of developments Friday after midnight strike was called by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> and Aerospace Workers against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BUSH-MEDIATION RECOMMENDATION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rejected a mediation board recommendation to use his authority under provisions of the Railway Labor Act and delay the strike for 60 more days. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also warned he would not tolerate sympathy strikes threatened by other unions to support the Machinists. Eastern wanted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to stay out of the dispute, saying either a strike, if it involved pilots, or postponement of the strike, would lead to bankruptcy. The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> and 33 senators had asked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to intervene to prevent `` a major disruption of interstate commerce.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>STRIKE PREPARATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Eastern said it would slash up to 75 percent of its weekend flights, including most services from its <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> hub and about 60 other cities. The airline said earlier that it was prepared to operate during any strike and had contracted with 1,100 non-union mechanics to service planes. Eastern's pilots rejected an appeal Thursday by airline owner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> for them to sign a new contract and cross Machinists picket lines. Flight attendants said they would honor picket lines. Airports nationwide strengthened security and other airlines have reported surges in sales this week.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MACHINISTS SENT HOME</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Eastern obtained a federal court order and sent its machinists home, saying the action was intended to prevent sabotage. Machinists were given a paid holiday and told to return to work for shifts starting at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday, one minute after the strike deadline. Eastern said management personnel would handle ground duties for the rest of the day.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NEGOTIATIONS END</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Eastern's offer Thursday was rejected Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, and federal officials said they expected a strike at the midnight deadline as talks continued between the airline and the union. Eastern said the contract offered would reduce mechanics' pay but still keep their salaries 13 percent higher than employees who took a 20 percent pay cut when <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> took over in 1986. It said baggage handlers' cuts would be no greater than those of other employees. At 12:01 a.m., the Machinists went on strike.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LABOR SUPPORT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> and other union leaders said they doubted there would be any settlement because <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> wants to dismantle <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which they said is worth about $ 500 million. Other unions pledged support in a plan to block work at other airlines, railways and sea transport companies if a strike is called. The <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> announced that in the event of an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> strike, it would instruct its 40,000 members beginning Tuesday to strictly follow procedures that would cause `` substantial delays.'' <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> AFL </ORGANIZATION>'s 14 million members should honor the Eastern pickets wherever they are legally set up. A federal court in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> enjoined <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> employees from staging a sympathy strike. Other airlines and the union won a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> order in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that banned picketing of companies other than Eastern.
</TEXT>
