<HEAD>Feds Order Airlines To Check Boeing 747 Cargo Doors Within 30 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> issued an emergency order on Friday, requiring all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines to reinforce latch mechanisms on <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 cargo doors within 30 days, so the doors are less vulnerable to damage from improper closing. The emergency Airworthiness Directive, which speeds up the timetable of an earlier directive, also specifies special inspections and tests of the doors that must be done until modifications are completed. The action Friday follows the Feb. 24 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> accident near <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> in which a 10-by-20-foot hole was torn in a 747 fuselage. Nine people were swept to their deaths. The cause of the accident has yet to be determined, but the possible failure of the forward cargo door latch is under investigation. The door separated from the aircraft with parts of the fuselage that surrounded it. The 747 order affects about 150 airplanes. However, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said some airlines have already made the required modifications, which include steel reinforcements to cargo door latches. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued a directive July 1 ordering the doors inspected and modified by the end of 1989 or July 1, 1990, depending on the type of locking mechanism installed. That order was issued after a cargo door on a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> 747 opened 1 -LCB- inches at the start of a flight from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said at the time the situation did not warrant an emergency directive. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> also said it soon would issue another Airworthiness Directive requiring improvements in the warning system that alerts flight crews when any cargo door is not properly closed and locked. The directive was expected as soon as the design improvements can be delivered and tested. There were similarities in the events on the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> planes. The cargo doors in both instances had to be closed by hand rather than electrically, after they had been malfunctioning. There were no warning lights to indicate whether the doors were open, said both flight crews. Additionally, the agency has formed a team to review all current <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> service bulletins on the 747 cargo door to determine whether instructions are complete and understandable, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said Friday in a statement issued in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. The team is focusing on the possibility of human error that might be associated with specific procedures. It is expected to complete its work within a week. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said changes made in the latest directive, from the July 1, 1988, order, included visual inspection of the cargo door latch before each flight, new torque limits on the door if it is closed manually, and shorter timetables for inspection for damage and of electrical systems. He said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> supported the action by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, and in fact had suggested in service bulletins of March and April 1987, the cargo door improvements that were included in the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s directive of July 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> also ordered immediate inspections of Dash 8-100 planes made by de Havilland of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, because faulty connections were found in fire-extinguishing systems on two of the Canadian-made Dash 8-100 airliners.
</TEXT>
