<HEAD>Space Shuttle Discovery Launch Set For March 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Discovery and its crew of five astronauts are scheduled to lift off March 11 on the first of seven shuttle flights set for 1989. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> selected the date Friday following a two-day review of the mission. Liftoff was set for 8:10 a.m. EST. `` Our launch teams are not working any significant issues which are expected to impact a launch next week,'' said Adm. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Truly </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s associate administrator for space flight, who directed the review. The mission will be the third for the shuttle program since the explosive loss of Challenger and its seven astronauts more than three years ago. Discovery made the first post-Challenger flight last September and was followed by an Atlantis flight in December. The latest launch originally was scheduled Feb. 18, but technical problems forced a series of delays. Discovery's crew, headed by commander <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>, is to deploy a large communications satellite and conduct scientific experiments during five days in orbit. Also on board will be astronauts <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaha </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagian </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>.
