<SECOND>AM-Fairchild,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Defense Calls Mentally Retarded Given Stay of Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Friday blocked the execution of a man after a defense attorney argued that the condemned man was mentally retarded and did not understand his rights when he was arrested. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairchild </PERSON>, 34, was scheduled to die by injection on Wednesday for the 1983 beating, rape and murder of a 22-year-old nurse. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisele </PERSON> ordered the stay after a two-hour hearing. Defense attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> cited intelligence tests Fairchild had taken which indicated that his client is mentally retarded. `` I knew the stay would be granted. I got the test results at 10 this morning,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said Friday. The attorney general's office said it would not appeal the stay to the 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Eisele </PERSON> set a hearing for March 16 to determine if Fairchild had the mental capacity to understand the nature of his rights and the consequences of his action when he waived his so-called Miranda rights after he was arrested. He signed and initialed the waiver, according to testimony at his trial. The Miranda rights include the suspect's right to keep silent; to be informed that anything he says may be used against him; to have an attorney present when he is questioned by police; and to have an attorney appointed for him free if he can not afford to hire one. Questioned about what his Miranda rights were, Fairchild described them during the hearing as `` remain silent, whatever say can be used against you, right to call a lawyer.'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said Fairchild is easily led to give particular answers, even though he does not realize the implications of what he is doing. He may not realize what it means for something to be used against him, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. Psychologist <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> testified for the defense that on the basis of testing Thursday at the prison, she would place Fairchild's IQ in the range of 56 to 64, which is considered mentally retarded. The IQ statistic differs from the previous figure that was determined after a 1986 test that said his IQ was 87, which is dull-normal. An elementary school test given to <LOCATION> Fairchild </LOCATION> some 24 years ago placed his IQ at 65, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Eisele </PERSON> encouraged Hall to conduct more in-depth tests and told the state to conduct any tests it desired. Fairchild was convicted in the death of <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, a Little Rock Air Force Base nurse. She was shot twice in the back of the head and her body was found behind an abandoned <LOCATION> Lonoke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> farmhouse. <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> has had no execution since 1964.
