<HEAD>Soviets in Balancing Act in Rushdie Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s offer to help cool the furor over the novel `` The Satanic Verses'' seems a careful attempt to balance its interests in improving relations with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the West and its own burgeoning Moslem population. The Soviets have defended <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> without condoning the campaign to kill the book's author. As 15 Western nations withdrew their top diplomats from <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> to protest <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death threat against <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> edged closer to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> while seeking to ease the uproar. `` We need calm,'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said Thursday as he greeted his Spanish counterpart. `` The less emotion the better for all at the present period. We have to extinguish -LRB- the fire -RRB- because nobody needs a fire.'' The Soviets have not revealed how the dispute could be resolved, but with an increasingly restive Moslem population of 50 million in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, they can ill afford a misstep. At first, Soviet officials declined comment on the dispute, although <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> was then visiting the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on his itinerary. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> ordered his followers Feb. 14 to kill <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, a naturalized British citizen, because of his book. Moslems say the book is blasphemous and Iranian clergymen have offered a $ 5.2 million bounty for <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s death. After <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> discussed the dispute with Iranian officials during a three-day trip to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> that ended Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said: `` The government of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is sincere about finding a settlement of the situation that has emerged, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could have a positive role to play.'' In elaborating the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s middle-ground position, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that Western countries were justified in their `` indignation'' over <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s threat. But, the news agency added: `` Perhaps Imam <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, the supreme religious authority in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, had no choice proceeding from Koran teachings, other than denouncing a man who has insulted Islam.'' `` The denunciation was nothing more, by the way, than the position of a religious leader. The Iranian government has not condemned <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> to death,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said, even though <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> officials have supported the threat. The sympathy toward <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s religious concerns was unusual in light of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s advocacy of atheism, but reflected sensitivity to its own Moslem population. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s Moslem population is growing much more rapidly than ethnic Russians who hold the reins of political power. Based on current trends, the Moslem population will rise to 100 million by the year 2000, meaning one in every three Soviets will be a Moslem. Soviet Moslems were unhappy when the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> moved into neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979 to fight Moslem rebels. Siding with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> in the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> dispute would have angered Soviet Moslems further at a time when they are becoming increasingly vocal. On Feb. 3, Moslems massed in the Uzbek capital of <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION> to demand the ouster of their religious leader because, they said, he was not following religious law and was a pawn of the state. He later resigned and Moslems are to choose a new leader March 14-15. In other signs of new sensitivity to Moslems, the government has promised to open more mosques and expand an Islamic seminary. After <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s meetings in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> sought to play down <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death threat even though the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had asked him to `` raise concerns with the Iranians'' and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> urged him to press <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to back off. For <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, however, further improving relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> carried the day. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> once lumped the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> together as `` The Great Satan.'' In a sign of the changing times, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> became the highest ranking Soviet to visit <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> since its 1979 Islamic revolution. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s relations with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> have improved markedly since it began allowing Moslems more religious freedom and withdrawing its troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, gratified by the Afghan pullout, signed an agreement in December to supply the Soviets with natural gas. Trade is growing between the countries, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is helping rebuild areas of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> devastated in its 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Aside from bringing it closer to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the Soviet offer of mediation in the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> affair serves a wider foreign policy goal. It is in line with President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` new political thinking,'' which seeks to avoid confrontation and stresses compromise and cooperation. The Soviet tabloid Arguments and Facts said Friday the affair opens a peacemaking opportunity for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` In such cases, more than ever, assistance is needed from a party that can take a sober view of things, to help both sides get out of the difficult situation they created,'' the newspaper said. Spanish Foreign Minister <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON>, who met Thursday in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> mediation effort had not yet begun. `` There was no proposal concerning an intermediary role,'' he said Friday. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> is slated to discuss the issue next week in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>.
