<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage-Table,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minimum Wage Levels Over the Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> set the first national minimum wage at 40 cents an hour in 1938 with the Fair Labor Standards Act. Since then, lawmakers have passed six amendments to the act, raising the minimum, the last time in 1977 when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> decided to raise the level gradually over four years to $ 3.35, the current mark. Here is a list of the increases: 1938 _ $ 0.40. 1949 _ $ 0.75. 1955 _ $ 1.00. 1961 _ $ 1.15. 1963 _ $ 1.25. 1966 _ $ 1.40. 1967 _ $ 1.60. 1974 _ $ 2.00. 1975 _ $ 2.10. 1976 _ $ 2.30. 1978 _ $ 2.65. 1979 _ $ 2.90. 1980 _ $ 3.10. 1981 _ $ 3.35. Twelve states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> have raised the minimum wage in laws that take precedence over the federal standard inside their borders, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> have the highest minimum at $ 4.25 an hour, although <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> has a $ 4.85 floor for some workers. The other states with minimums higher than the federal government are <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
