<SECOND>PM-Aryan Woodstock, Bjt,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Against ``Aryan Woodstock,'' But Gathering Allowed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Gathering starts at 11 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAPA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Skinheads and white supremacists refused to back down from a rally on a private ranch today, but they abandoned plans for a whites-only `` Aryan Woodstock'' rock concert that a judge said required a permit. `` We can sing, we just ca n't play instruments,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Heick </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> head of a white supremacist group called <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> who represented concert organizers in court Friday. `` I'm not angry,'' he said. `` I expected this, obviously.'' <ORGANIZATION> Napa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Snowden </PERSON>, describing the issue as `` politically and emotionally charged,'' deemed the event a public gathering. He issued a restraining order prohibiting the concert because organizers had failed to obtain a permit required by county ordinance. But <PERSON> Snowden </PERSON> allowed a public gathering, rejecting the county's argument that the assembly would be a public nuisance and saying it `` demonstrated no clear and present danger to the public. Six skinheads linked arms around <LOCATION> Heick </LOCATION> and escorted him out of the courthouse, using lighted cigarettes to make their way through a throng of reporters. <PERSON> Heick </PERSON> vowed to `` get a concert going'' elsewhere. Leaders of the groups said they would gather today to party and discuss their `` white liberation movement.'' The site is a private ranch about 40 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The physican who owns the land and leased it for the gathering said he was told the meeting was to be about environmental concerns. The skinhead subculture and style of dress emerged in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in the 1960s. Segments of the movement later took on Nazi overtones and since have been associated with the white supremacist groups. County attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Westmeyer </PERSON> said the ruling did n't surprise him, adding that it might prompt the county Board of Supervisors to change the law. `` I think -LRB- they -RRB- may consider revising the ordinance to apply to large public gatherings, rather than just rock concerts,'' he said. Before the hearing, an <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> official warned that the gathering was an effort to win support for an unpopular cause which advocates racial violence. However, Regional Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> would not `` dignify the existence of this group or their planned event with our presence tommorrow.'' `` We can ignore a rock concert by skinheads, but we can not ignore what they represent in terms of potential danger,'' he added. The Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> and the anti-crime <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angels </ORGANIZATION> civilian patrol group indicated they would demonstrate at the rally. <PERSON> Heick </PERSON>, who sports 16 tattoos, including SKINS inked inside his lower lip, said during Friday's hearing that, `` Our intention was to comply with the law.'' He said a check with the county some time ago indicated no permit was needed. `` In no way would we want a public event,'' he said. `` We wanted to keep out of people's way, where we could all be alone and have a little party.'' The concert was to feature skinhead bands Midtown Boot Boys from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, the Hammerheads from <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hakenkreuz </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Organizer <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> leader and currently head of a group called <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION>, argued earlier that since the concert was to be held on private property and admission was by invitation only, no permit was needed. Although <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> earlier had predicted as many as 2,000 people might attend the concert, <PERSON> Heick </PERSON> on Friday said he expected about 200 attendees.
