<HEAD>International Economic Aid Earmarked For Riot-Torn Venezuela</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other Western nations are putting together emergency loans to help <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> weather an economic crisis that sparked nationwide riots and the deaths this week of at least 300 people. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> on Friday linked the bloodiest civil unrest in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s history to the burden of its foreign debt. He said debt payments threaten the newest democracies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He accused foreign debtors of inflexibility by demanding repayment of the region's $ 420 billion foreign debt without regard to a nation's ability to pay. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> owes international banks and lenders $ 33 billion _ fourth largest in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. `` I hope this painful sacrifice by our country will serve for the leaders of the industrial powers to reflect that we are not exaggerating when we say the crisis is serious,'' the 66-year-old leader said. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced Friday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would provide <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> with a $ 450 million bridge loan to help <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> meet its short-term financial needs. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> also Friday said it would loan <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> $ 50 million. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was making the loan to help ease the financial crisis facing <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>' month-old government. The loans are part of an overall package from countries including <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> as well as from international lenders, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said in today's editions. Quoting government and banking officials, it said the emergency loans will total nearly $ 2 billion. The rioting and looting in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> and seven other cities was touched off by government-imposed hikes in bus fares and fuel, which appeared to release pent-up frustration over the country's austerity program. Perez on Friday confirmed at least 300 people had been killed and 2,000 injured since the unrest flared Monday. He put the number of arrests at `` barely 1,000.'' The <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> today quoted unofficial sources as saying an estimated 350 to 500 people had died in four days of rioting. The newspaper said more than 2,000 had been arrested in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>. Curfew hours were shortened Friday from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. to 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. as the rioting ended, although early today soldiers and police exchanged sporadic gunfire with snipers in some low-income <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> neighborhoods. The Federation of University Students said 31 people were missing and alleged that <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> patrols had executed people dragged out of homes. The student group accused police of conducting indiscriminant searches and arrests of student and labor leaders in areas where no riots were reported. There was no immediate government response to the charges. Speaking at his news conference Friday, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said whether <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> can continue to make principal and interest payments on its foreign debt depends on the success of his austerity program. `` The crisis Latin American nations are undergoing has a name written with capital letters _ foreign debt,'' he said. Other nations facing similar economic crises include <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, where a battle in January between rebels and the army claimed 39 lives, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said. In a question-and-answer session with reporters, the president appeared to indicate that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> had already suspended the debt payments. However, Venezuelan officials later Friday said there had been differing interpretations of his remarks and that the payments would be kept up at least until the end of the month. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> was referring to economic austerity measures required under an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> exchange </ORGANIZATION> for a $ 4.3 billion loan over the next three years. Earlier this week, the government asked the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to include provisions allowing <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> to suspend all payments on its debt until September. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> is one of the few developing nations that has been servicing foreign debt, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said, complaining that Western banks had not recognized the effort by granting new loans. Oil-producing <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> has for decades been one of the wealthiest and most politically stable nations in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. But a fall in world oil prices since 1981, combined with debt payments, has depleted monetary reserves. Real wages have fallen by a third since 1981, and inflation is expected to double this year to 70 percent.
