<HEAD>Pennsylvania Declares Drought Warning In Eastern Counties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state disaster agency has declared a drought warning for 16 eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> counties in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> basin </LOCATION> and asked people to cut water consumption. Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Singel </PERSON>, who chairs the state <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday the shortfall in precipitation and seriously low reservoirs forced the action. `` It's good policy ... and prudent water management,'' <PERSON> Singel </PERSON> said. `` It will go a long way to relieving a situation that may be critical in July.'' People in eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> are urged to cut water consumption by 10 percent by taking such steps as checking for water leaks in their homes and curbing the use of washing machines and dishwashers. <PERSON> Singel </PERSON> said problems could start as early as next month if conservation steps are not taken now. The next step would be a drought emergency with enforced water cutbacks. More than 20 million people in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> depend upon the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for their water supply, <PERSON> Singel </PERSON> said, and rainfall in the river's basin during the past six months has averaged 4 to 6 inches below normal.
