<HEAD>Protesting Nuns Ordered Out Of Convent Say They Won't Go</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five nuns protesting the liberalization of their order plan to spend a sixth month barricaded in their monastery unless they are convinced of the legitimacy of a <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> directive to stop. The nuns have refused since Oct. 4 to leave the monastery's infirmary until the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> ruled in the dispute The nuns said they feared their mother superior would evict them before the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> had a chance to review their case. A spokeswoman for the nuns said Friday they did n't believe the ruling delivered to them by Roman Catholic Bishop <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodimer </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, diocese was legitimate and that they would continue their protest. `` Nothing came here with a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> seal on it,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, the spokeswoman. `` It's the bishop's final trick to get them out.'' The Rev. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said an appeal to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s highest court, the Apostolica Signatura, could take two weeks or more to be decided. Two of the women whose temporary five-year vows expired during the protest were told they must leave the Monastery of the Most Blessed <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Paterson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diocese </ORGANIZATION> announced. Two others were told they should seek residence in a different convent, and the fifth, a 71-year-old nun who suffers heart problems, was told she would be allowed to stay at the monastery, said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Rodimer </PERSON>. The five nuns were among 13 cloistered members of the Order of Discalced Carmelites at the monastery. The nuns said they wanted the monastery returned to the Carmelites' traditionally austere lifestyle. They had objected to the introduction of such modern elements as television and candy. `` Despite the difficult situation created by some of the religious, the fundamental principles of religious life were firmly retained with prudence and charity,'' read the ruling from Cardinal <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamer </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congregation </ORGANIZATION> for the Religious, which oversees religious communities. <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> said he did not know if the five nuns would be forcibly removed if they refused to leave. The mother superior, Prioress Mother <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, called the standoff a `` scandal'' when the nuns took over the infirmary and criticized the unruly members of her order for disrupting the cloistered lifestyle. <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rodimer </PERSON> have said the controversy centered on the rebel nuns' inability to follow their mother superior's orders. Sister <PERSON> Eliane </PERSON>, a nun who has acted as a spokeswoman for those not involved in the protest, said she had no immediate comment. `` Not now, not yet,'' she said, adding that the others did not want to comment. Mrs. <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said all five women still considered themselves nuns and part of the order and that they planned to stay until they heard from the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s highest court. `` We entered the monastery for a particular lifestyle, and what these other, liberal nuns, did is change these rules,'' Sister <PERSON> John </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, one of the barricaded nuns whose temporary vows expired, said in a telephone interview shortly after the nuns took over the infirmary. `` We would n't be doing this unless we were desperate.''
