<HEAD>Judge Rules Florida Town's Voting System Discriminates Against Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has sided with blacks who claimed that the town of <PERSON> Starke </PERSON>'s at-large voting policy has effectively shut them out of local government. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON>, noting that the Starke charter still contains a residential segregation clause, concluded in his 42-page order filed Monday that blacks `` have suffered from pervasive racial discrimination.'' He gave each side 30 days to propose remedies. City Attorney <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> had argued during trial in June that the at-large system benefited all <PERSON> Starke </PERSON> residents and the north <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> town of 5,300 people was too small to divide into districts. But attorneys representing a group of black residents and the <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> branch of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, who filed the lawsuit in 1986, said citywide voting for city commission members has shut out <PERSON> Starke </PERSON>'s black residents, who represent 32 percent of the voting population. <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON> found that although city services have not been denied to blacks, political opportunity has been in both elective and appointive positions. `` Perhaps the clearest example of city-sponsored discrimination can be found in the city charter of 1927,'' the judge wrote. The provision, still on the books but not enforced for years, requires that blacks reside in the northeast section of the town, known locally as <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>. `` The lingering effects of this historical racial discrimination are evident by the fact that blacks today continue to be segregated by custom in the northeastern quadrant of the city,'' the judge's order said If <PERSON> Starke </PERSON>'s at-large voting system is allowed to remain, it `` will continue to deny blacks equal access to the city's political process,'' he wrote. <PERSON> Starke </PERSON> has held at-large elections for its five city commissioners, one of whom serves as mayor, and for the city clerk and police chief. `` We're hoping we can settle as far as drawing the lines up without any further battle,'' said <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Spooner </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Bradford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> and one of the plaintiffs in the lawsuit. `` I would hope that both sides can sit down and work out an agreement that is acceptable to both and get down to running city government,'' said City Commissioner <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>. The next local elections are scheduled for fall.
