k any laws.'' A few union members lurched for the fence, but were pulled back by union leaders. Then car horns blared. Workers heading back to union headquarters blocked traffic for nearly 10 minutes as an effigy of a `` scab worker'' was torn apart. The legs of the dummy were tossed above the crowd. The head rested on the hood of a pickup truck. `` I hope <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is watching,'' said <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>. `` The message is pretty obvious.'' After the display, police moved in and herded workers back onto union property. Twenty-five minutes after midnight, the first of the workers began to leave. `` I think we made our point,'' said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, a 21-year mechanic suspended without pay for a month following wildcat walkouts in February. `` It was really just for show.'' `` It was loud, but pretty peaceful,'' said <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> police spokeswoman <PERSON> Myriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Royale </PERSON>. No arrests were made, no injuries were reported and no damage was found, she said. Two hours into the strike, most of the workers had left the union headquarters and pickets were under way at Eastern headquarters, terminals and cargo facilities. `` We're going to keep this peaceful,'' said <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Haber </PERSON>, senior general chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>' <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> local. `` We just needed to let off some steam.''
