<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A businessman linked to the governing Socialists has been charged with insider trading, making him the sixth person accused in a scandal that has embarrassed the government, a news report said. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Theret </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> investor who has backed <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidates, was charged Friday by Investigating Magistrate <PERSON> Edith </PERSON> <PERSON> Boizette </PERSON> with insider trading, the news agency <ORGANIZATION> Agence-France </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> said. Quoting unidentified legal sources, the agency said <PERSON> Theret </PERSON> is accused of illegally buying shares of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company, <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, before the French state-owned aluminum manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Pichiney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> offered a higher price in a successful takeover. The Pichiney offer sent the stock's price soaring. On Feb. 16, three men also were charged with insider trading: <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> stockbrokers <PERSON> Pierre-Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Reiplinger </PERSON>, Theret's partner in a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> investment firm. Also charged in the scandal that day was <PERSON> Roger-Patrice </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelat </PERSON>, a retired businessman and longtime friend of President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. Theret was not charged with the others because he had been hospitalized with a heart ailment. French law requires that an investigating magistrate notify a suspect face-to-face of criminal charges. <PERSON> Pelat </PERSON> and a friend, <PERSON> Isabelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierco </PERSON>, have been charged with rec