<HEAD>Feds Order Airlines To Check Boeing 747 Cargo Doors Within 30 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has issued an emergency order requiring all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines to reinforce latch mechanisms on <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 cargo doors within 30 days. Friday's emergency airworthiness directive, which speeds up the timetable of an earlier directive, also specifies inspections and tests of the doors that must be done until modifications are completed. The action Friday follows the Feb. 24 accident involving a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet that had taken off from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> in which a 10-by 20-foot hole ripped in the fuselage and nine people were sucked from the craft. They are presumed dead. Though the cause of the accident has yet to be determined, the possible failure of the forward cargo door latch is under investigation. The door was separated from the aircraft with parts of the fuselage that surrounded it. The order affects about 150 airplanes. However, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said some airlines have already made the required modifications, which include steel reinforcements to cargo door latches. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> had issued a directive last July 1 ordering the doors inspected and modified by the end of 1989 or July 1, 1990, depending on the type of locking mechanism installed. That order was issued after a cargo door on a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> 747 opened 1 -LCB- inches at the start of a flight from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said they did n't believe at the time the situation warranted an emergency directive. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> also said it planned to issue another airworthiness directive in the near future requiring improvements in the warning system that alerts flight crews when any cargo door is not properly closed and locked. That order was expected as soon as the design improvements can be delivered and tested.
