<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bodies are lying in morgues, sometimes for years, while their survivors negotiate for money and jobs as compensation from the dead relative's workplace, an official daily said today. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said survivors of a worker at the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Theater Troupe have refused to let the body be cremated until the troupe agrees to provide two apartments and a job for one of the children. A second case was cited in the report of the body of a woman that has been kept at one hospital for more than five years because the family and her work unit ca n't agree on compensation. It also said in another hospital run by the military that 100 of the 500 bodies in the morgue had been there more than two months. The daily quoted a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official as saying state-run work units must pay pensions to children too young to support themselves if their parents die or are seriously injured on the job. However, there are no regulations saying children can take their parent's job, the report said. The official was quoted as saying, `` Chinese people are too dependent on the government and their work units.'' He said the Chinese `` should develop their abilities to support themselves in society.''
