When I first saw that document, it took 60 seconds to ascertain through computer records that those -LRB- certificates -RRB- were not missing.'' Earlier Friday, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> was asked about the certificates at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Judiciary immigration subcommitte hearing in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> told the panel's chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., he first learned of the supposedly missing certificates from the Justice audit The commissioner said he did n't know about the finding until he read the audit. In Friday editions, the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported that <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> auditors found serious instances of mismanagement, including the episode involving the missing certificates. The audit said <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> could n't account for them more than a year after investigators discovered them missing, and the agency took no steps to prevent further losses. The report also said that two years after investigators found at least 61,500 naturalized citizens had n't turned in their permanent resident alien cards, the agency had not tried to recover them.
