<HEAD>Town Raises Money, Police Officers Recalled</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> MCKEESPORT </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> _ Twenty-one officers laid off from this <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> suburb's 50-member police force will resume work Sunday thanks to a successful fund-raising campaign to pay their salaries. `` The response has been overwhelming,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON>, who announced the recall. `` McKeesport residents and people outside the city have continued to support the police. ... When asked, they've always responded.'' Donations reached $ 106,000 on Friday, including a bank's pledge to match donations dollar for dollar, <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, chief of the emergency medical services. Shoppers were still dropping coins and bills into cans at local businesses, and a number of fund-raising events were scheduled for this weekend, including dances, a basketball game and a health fair. `` We've received checks from all over the country, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, virtually everywhere,'' <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said. `` These are people who lived here 30, 40 years ago and people who never knew how to spell McKeesport.'' Police Chief <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brletic </PERSON> expressed relief as he drafted work schedules. He had to make do without the officers since they were let go last Sunday. `` This past week, while it's been very busy, the good Lord must have been watching us because we did n't have anything terrible happen,'' he said. The mayor had asked all employees to accept a wage freeze after the city discovered a $ 1.3 million deficit late last year. He had said layoffs would result if the request were refused. <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON> announced the layoffs Feb. 1, saying they were necessary because state arbitrators awarded the police pay raises of 4 percent to 4.5 percent. He said the city would save $ 90,000 by laying off 21 officers for three months. The city's volunteer ambulance company, <ORGANIZATION> McKeesport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, launched the fund-raising drive with a $ 15,000 donation Feb. 24. <PERSON> Washowich </PERSON> said the success of the fund-raiser wo n't solve the city's long-term money woes, however. `` I'm sorry to say the reality will set in,'' he said. `` Next year we have to find $ 200,000 to $ 220,000.''
