<HEAD>Shadowy Youth Gang Comes To Symbolize NYC Street Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City high school students are taking lessons in fear these days, and their teachers are the Decepticons _ a loosely organized gang of young thugs who have assumed near-mythical status. While the gang, which preys largely on fellow teen-agers, is responsible for only a small part of youth crime in the city, educators say its impact goes far beyond its reality. `` The idea of the Decepticons has a lot of power over the kids. It's a symbol of something bad. Like, ` the boogey man is coming, the Decepticons are coming,''' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, formerly a <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> principal and now the superintendent of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> high schools. The drug rings that have gradually replaced most of the city's old neighborhood-based youth gangs are more violent and make a lot more money But the `` Decepts,'' who emerged about three years ago and named themselves after a group of cartoon characters, have gained a unique hold on the imagination of high school students as a horde of rowdies preying on easy victims near schools, taking anything from earrings to expensive sneakers. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said the mere rumor that the Decepticons were going to invade her <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> high school a couple of years ago brought the police out and prompted many parents to keep their children at home. The Decepts failed to show up; in fact, they've never been known to actually invade a school building. A group of students leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> several days ago all knew of the Decepticons' reputation and said many teen-agers feared them `` They steal bus passes, sneakers, gold jewelry, anything,'' said one boy who declined to give his name. But he and the other youths said they had never actually encountered the Decepticons and knew no one who had. There are 56 known members of the Decepticons, including 14 girls who call themselves Deceptinets, police said. Gang members, who come from all over the city and range in age from 15 to 22, typically hang out near a school during lunch breaks or after classes and occasionally mug a vulnerable youngster. They generally gather first at a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> high school and then commute to <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> where they can seek victims around several high schools along the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> subway lines, said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Muir </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> safety committee. The Decepticons have attained their notoriety largely because `` they're the only game in town,'' <PERSON> Muir </PERSON> said. Drug rings, with their tremendous profits, lure most of the youths who would have been drawn to the old-style gangs and their turf battles, authorities say. `` You can certainly make a lot more money by selling drugs to kids than by stealing their sneakers,'' <PERSON> Muir </PERSON> said. During the early 1970s, the city had some 400 youth gangs with nearly 20,000 members. The police now know of 37 gangs with about 1,000 members, said Sgt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Galea </PERSON>, head of the police department's youth gang intelligence unit The Decepticons, named for fiendish, missile-hurling cartoon characters on television's `` The Transformers,'' are the largest and by far the most notorious of the remaining youth gangs. The Decepts wear no insignia or gang colors and dress like many other teens in designer clothes, expensive leather basketball shoes and lots of gold jewelry. They dress like other city youngsters, <PERSON> Galea </PERSON> explained, `` because they steal the other kids' clothes.'' They arm themselves with ax handles, hammers, box cutters, occasionally knives, but they rarely carry guns, <PERSON> Galea </PERSON> said. Almost exclusively, their victims are their peers. Five Decepticons were arrested on assault charges last year, and gang members were charged in 43 robberies, mostly involving thefts of clothing and jewelry, police said. The reality of the gang is that it exists. The mythology is that it is everywhere in large numbers, <PERSON> Galea </PERSON> said: `` We have reports that they're going to invade schools in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, all in the same day.'' <PERSON> Galea </PERSON> says the Decepticons are responsible for only a `` very, very small portion of youth crime.'' But the gang has a strong hold on the imaginations of many students who use the term `` Decepts'' for any group of violent teens. `` Their name is by far the most infamous; it does elicit fear,'' <PERSON> Galea </PERSON> said. `` As the kids travel throughout the city, this is the name they hear.''
