<HEAD>Arguments Over Classified Documents Tie Up North Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers have been complaining since the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide was indicted that national security concerns were imposing unfair restrictions on the defense. Last week, they found an outlet for their frustration. North's courier to the Contras, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, wrote memos outlining the military needs of the guerrilla force and the names of some Central American officials assisting them. The government censored portions of some of the memos for use at <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>'s trial, but last Monday night, <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers found out that uncensored versions of the memos had become public eight months ago in a civil case. Adding fuel to the fire was the fact that two lawyers and the security chief in the office of independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> had been told Feb. 10 about the dissemination of the uncensored memos. On Tuesday, <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers filed a motion to dismiss the indictment based on prosecutorial misconduct and renewed old motions that the Classified Information Procedures Act should be declared unconstitutional as applied to <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s case. On Friday, instead of the trial, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> held a hearing on <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s motions on constitutionality. He plans to rule this week. At the hearing, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> both criticized <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers for demanding too much disclosure and sought to reassure them. There can be cross-examination without disclosing `` every name, every security technique, every secret code that's in the case,'' said <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>. At another point, he said: `` I do n't want to kill anybody ... but beyond that ... you have an open door'' to disclose a substantial amount of sensitive material, a comment that should give <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agencies pause. The tension between national security concerns and <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s right to a fair trial promises to plague the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide's case to the end The trial _ in which opening statements were Feb. 21 _ could last up to five months. Tuesday afternoon found one of the prosecutors in the case, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bromwich </PERSON>, sitting in the witness box trying to explain what happened after <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>'s lawyer mentioned to him Feb. 10 that he had given uncesored copies of the memos last June to the <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an activist group opposed to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy toward <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bromwich </PERSON> said he informed the security officer in his office and then never gave the matter another thought. The other prosecutor present in the meeting also moved on to other matters, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>, chief of the prosecution team in the North case. The security officer, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stansbury </PERSON>, said he decided to wait until after the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> security chief returned from vacation before taking any action to retrieve the memos. No one else was told, including <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers. North attorney <PERSON> Brendan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> had been cross-examining <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> on Monday and had objected to the prohibition of the use of a high Costa Rican official's name in one of the Owen memos. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> met with the official while on an inspection trip for a possible site for an airstrip. The prosecution found out late Monday night that the news media was getting uncensored versions of the memos. Prosecutors quickly obtained approval from intelligence agencies to authorize unrestricted use at trial of the ones deemed relevant to <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s defense However, the damage was done. `` An evidentiary hearing should be held to determine when the IC was first aware of the production of documents to the <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, what efforts if any the IC made to prevent disclosure to the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, why the fact of public disclosure was withheld from the defense and the court while these matters were being hotly litigated in the course of Mr. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>'s cross-examination, and all other relevant information,'' said <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. Problems have arisen repeatedly in the case in connection with classified material and the law that governs its use. The prosecution was forced to seek dismissal of the conspiracy and theft counts in the indictment because attempting to prove them in court would have required disclosure of more classified material than intelligence agencies were willing to allow. The prosecution has been helped somewhat by the pre-trial disclosure provisions of federal law concerning use of classified material at trial. North's lawyers have been required to notify the government of all the classified documents they plan to use in court. Also required was a 162-page summary of classified testimony the defense plans to present. When the defense declined to explain what counts of the indictment to which it planned to tie the material, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> declared he was unable to rule on its admissibility and said he would rule as the trial proceeds. That approach triggered such serious concern in the intelligence community that on Feb. 9, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> began trying to delay the trial, while prosecutors declared their intention to proceed. The impasse was resolved when <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s office agreed to establish a notification mechanism under which the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would be told anytime particularly sensitive information was about to be presented by the defense in court. The procedure would provide the government an opportunity to object.
