<HEAD>Three Neo-Fascists Arrested in Prison Break Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities said Saturday they arrested three members of a right-wing terror group in connection with a plot to stage a prison break at a maximum-security prison. Police said the three were arrested Thursday afternoon when they claimed a suitcase at a suburban train station that contained a submachine gun, a pistol, ammunition, police uniforms and fake Italian army license plates. Italian news agencies said police identified the trio as <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Inzillo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gianluca </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponzio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Angelis </PERSON>, all 26 and all from <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. Police said they are members of the Armed Revolutionary Nucleus terror group. Three other people were arrested Feb. 18 in connection with the planned break from Rebibbia prison. Police said one of the three arrested in February, <PERSON> Luca </PERSON> <PERSON> Onesti </PERSON>, 33, tried to swallow a piece of paper that contained details of the plot. Authorities said the note outlined a plan to conceal explosives inside cakes and smuggle them into certain inmates at the prison, which is on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. The plot was reportedly aimed at freeing some prisoners with rightist sympathies and some imprisoned for violent crimes. It did not say how many inmates were supposed to be freed.
