<HEAD>Samuel Beckett Emerges from Silence with Meditation on Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In his 83rd year, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON> has emerged from a studied silence with a brief novella, a meditation on old age that a reviewer praised as `` another of <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>'s nihilistic mantras, best mumbled aloud.'' Only 200 copies of `` Stirrings Still,'' the 1,801-word new work by the Nobel Prize-winning author of `` Waiting for Godot,'' are being printed. They are offered for sale at $ 1,720 each. `` The way they've gone this morning, they'll be gone by next week,'' publisher <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Calder </PERSON> said Friday, after the entire novella was published in The Guardian newspaper. The signed, limited edition includes illustrations by the Irish artist <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBrocquy </PERSON>, who also illustrated an edition of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>'s `` Dubliners,'' <PERSON> Calder </PERSON> said. A mass-market edition will be published, he said, but not for a couple of years. <PERSON> Calder </PERSON> said `` Stirrings Still'' was written in response to pleas from <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>'s American publisher, <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossett </PERSON>, formerly of <ORGANIZATION> Grove </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, though there are no immediate plans to print it in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It is a tale, reviewer <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Kermode </PERSON> wrote in The Guardian, that is typical <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON> _ `` of a featureless man in a virtually featureless world, expressing a condition in which everything that characterizes some of our normal assumptions about human existence ... is virtually annulled, in prose rich only its unmatched parsimony.'' Given the price, <PERSON> Kermode </PERSON> said, `` purchasers can henceforth meditate the destitution of their existence and simultaneously take pleasure in their privilege.'' This paragraph is typical of the style of the opus: `` A clock afar struck the hours and half-hours. The same as when among others <PERSON> Darly </PERSON> once died and left him. Strokes now clear as if carried by a wind now faint on the still air. Cries afar now faint now clear. Head on hands half hoping when the hour struck that the half-hour would not and half fearing that it would not. Similarly when the half-hour struck. Similarly when the cries a moment ceased. Or merely wondering. Or merely waiting. Waiting to hear.'' Born in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> and educated at <ORGANIZATION> Trinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1928 and became acquainted with <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, the Irish novelist and poet who became the subject of <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>'s first published essay a year later. <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON> eventually decided to live in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, saying he preferred `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in war to <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> in peace.'' He has continued to live in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, writing both in French and English. His last work, <PERSON> Calder </PERSON> said, was a novella titled `` Worstword Ho'' in 1982. `` Stirrings Still'' is hardly <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>'s most concise work. `` Breath,'' a 1969 theater piece, consisted of a pile of rubbish, a breath and a cry, lasting no more than 30 seconds.
