<HEAD>Three Dead In Chain Collision Caused By Blowing Dust, Unknown Motorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOWIE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A motorist who stopped on a highway during a blinding dust storm is believed to have started a chain reaction collision of 31 vehicles in which three people were killed, police said. At least 40 people were injured. The motorist who stopped in a traffic lane on Interstate 10 in southeastern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> was not involved in the accident, and drove away before anyone recorded his license number, the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> said. Officer <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Pittman </PERSON> said eight tractor-trailer rigs, a Greyhound bus and 22 cars were involved in the accident in the middle of the afternoon Friday. `` It was total black. You could n't see the road,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Host </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the driver of a tractor-trailer rig that struck the Greyhound bus. He suffered only a bruised arm. Wreckage was still being cleared away Saturday. The entire front of the bus, en route from <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, was sheared off when it collided with another vehicle after being struck from the rear by <ORGANIZATION> Host </ORGANIZATION>'s truck. `` You do n't have no protection up there -LRB- in the driver's seat -RRB-,'' said bus driver <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. Black, 43. `` It's just fiberglass and thin metal. I'm very glad to be alive.'' Black, of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, said most of his 25 passengers were treated for minor injuries. A bus official said a pregnant woman was admitted to a hospital for observation. <PERSON> Rik </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, 36, was on his way from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in his new pickup. He said he saw a jackknifed tractor-trailer on the road in front of him, and started pulling off toward a ditch on the left. `` Then I looked in the rear-view mirror and saw a bus skidding toward me,'' he said. `` I opened the door to get away. I was just out the door when the bus hit my truck.'' `` If I had been in the vehicle, my head would have gone right through the windshield,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. At least two of the dead were believed to be out-of-state truckers, <PERSON> Pittman </PERSON> said. The injured were taken to hospitals in <LOCATION> Willcox </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>.
