<HEAD>Ferry Capsizes, 23 Reported Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A crowded ferry capsized Saturday in southern <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, and at least 23 people drowned and many others were missing, news reports said. Three bodies were recovered from the hull of the ferry after rescue teams hauled the boat out of the swift flowing currents of the Kancha river, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> said. The other 20 bodies were found during a search of the accident site, <ORGANIZATION> UNB </ORGANIZATION> said. The accident occurred near <LOCATION> Hularhat </LOCATION>, a town 85 miles south of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>. The ferry was designed to carry 85 people but actually carried 200 people and 26,400 pounds of rice, authorities told the news agency. The weight caused the ferry to lose balance and overturn in the river. The news agency said some people were missing, but it did not give a specific figure. It said rescue operations were hampered by swift currents.
