<HEAD>Detroit Newspaper Merger Blocked by Supreme Court Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice on Saturday blocked, at least until March 17, the partial merger of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two daily newspapers that was to begin Monday. Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, in an unexpected move, said the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and The Detroit News may not start the partial merger until the full <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> considers the issue at its next regularly scheduled closed-door conference, March 17. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> on Friday had refused to postpone the partial merger, and lawyers for opponents to the deal then turned to <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> for help. Reporters initially had been told that <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> was not going to act on the emergency request before Monday. A federal appeals court panel here voted 2-1 to uphold then-Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision to allow the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> papers to form a joint operating agreement under the federal Newspaper Preservation Act. The 1970 law empowers the attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an exemption from antitrust laws. Under the joint operating agreement, the two <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newspapers would combine their business, advertising and production departments but maintain separate news and editorial staffs. By a 5-4 vote last month, the full appeals court refused to reconsider the three-judge panel's Jan. 27 ruling. The appeals court blocked the partial merger until March 6 so opponents could seek a longer delay from <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>. That delay was denied Friday. But <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, in a three-paragraph order issued Saturday, said he was referring the matter to the full court. His order added, `` It is further ordered that the order staying implementation of the joint operating agreement issued ... by the -LRB- appeals court -RRB- is continued pending further order of the court.'' A group of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> readers and advertisers who sued to stop the partial merger contend that the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, a morning newspaper owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is not a failing newspaper even though it lost $ 10 million a year between 1981 and 1986. The opponents, calling themselves <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, say the Free Press and News, which lost $ 50 million in the same period, were unprofitable solely because both papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out of business. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the News, is the nation's largest newspaper publishing group. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> is the second largest. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has threatened to close down the Free Press if the joint operating agreement is not approved. The opponents' emergency request said the agreement `` threatens the independence of daily newspapers in 25 cities'' where, like <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, competing newspapers still exist. The case is <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an Independent Press. vs. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, A-695.
