<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with as many as 12 dead. Pickup
8th graf pvs, ``A spokesman...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two passenger trains collided outside <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today in an accident that killed up to 12 people, injured about 50 and sent carriages careening into the gardens of trackside homes, authorities and witnesses said. Authorities said one train hit the back of the other near the Purley station in <LOCATION> Surrey </LOCATION>, on the southern outskirts of the capital. One train remained on the track but seven cars from the other fell down an embankment into the gardens, the Fire Brigade said. There was no indication anyone was hurt in the houses, but firefighters had to cut dozens of passengers free from the wreckage. There were conflicting casualty reports. About five hours after the 1:39 p.m. crash, the emergency room chief at nearby <LOCATION> Mayday </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kambiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON>, said four people died there and six at the scene. The bodies of two women were reported at nearby <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Helier </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, but it was not clear whether they were included among those dead at the scene. The Fire Brigade and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> said two people died. Fire officials put the injury toll at 50. British Rail said 32 people were injured. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION> said it appeared that one train, traveling north to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Horsham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sussex </LOCATION>, had been crossing from the local line to a fast track when it collided with a train bound for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Littlehampton </LOCATION>, on the south coast of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` We presume at this stage that the other -LRB- <LOCATION> Littlehampton </LOCATION> -RRB- train was already on the fast lane but we do not know how they impacted,'' the spokesman said. On Dec. 12, a three-train crash near <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Clapham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION> station, 10 miles to the north of today's accident, killed 35 people. Railroad officials blamed malfunctioning signals for that crash. In today's accident, one train ran into the back of another, plowed to one side, and slid down the steep embankment, Fire Brigade divisional officer <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Park </PERSON> said. Seven carriages `` slid away and turned over,'' he said. <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON> <PERSON> Muggeridge </PERSON>, 16, who was waiting on the <LOCATION> Purley </LOCATION> platform, said: `` A slow train was coming toward <LOCATION> Purley </LOCATION> station. A faster one came up behind it and seemed to clip the back of it. `` Three carriages from the first train rolled down the embankment and others stayed on the tracks but they were twisted and tilted. `` There was a very loud crash after the collision followed by an eerie silence. Then doors of the train started to open and there were shouts from inside the carriages.'' People ran from their homes and helped evacuate some of the injured. Other injured made their own way to safety, some apparently driven to hospital by a man who had his car parked in the street. Ambulance crews raced to the scene and hospitals went on alert. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was `` very distressed'' to hear of the train crash and was being kept informed of developments, said a spokesman for her 10 Downing St. office. A public inquiry is currently under way into a Dec. 12 crash. State-run <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> has blamed its own flawed system in installing new signaling equipment for the crash. Railway officials believe malfunctioning signals led one commuter train to slam into the rear of another that was stopped on the tracks. An empty freight train on an adjacent line then plowed into the wreckage and apparently hit some passengers who had scrambled onto the tracks. The <PERSON> Clapham </PERSON> crash was the worst train wreck in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since 1975, when 43 people died in a subway train that crashed in a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> tunnel.
