<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of police occupied hospitals in the country's four main cities on Saturday to keep regular medical services running during a five-day strike by hospital workers. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> sent police armed with tear gas and M-16 rifles into the hospitals late Friday and ordered 4,000 nurses, cooks and administrators to return to work by Monday or lose their jobs. No violence was reported. `` Our purpose is to open the hospitals so that the employee who wants to work can do so,'' <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said Friday. `` The ones who do n't do it will be sanctioned or fired and immediately replaced by someone who wants to work for the benefit of the people.'' He said the strikers, who are demanding higher wages, were `` violating the constitution by not attending to the public health.'' He and Public Health Minister <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Villeda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> said the workers would lose their jobs if the strike did not end by Monday morning. <PERSON> Celeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Casildo </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said the strike would continue. Since Tuesday, employees have been giving only emergency care while hundreds of people wait outside for non-emergency attention. `` We will continue defending our rights to the end,'' he said. `` The government promised to increase our salaries ... and it tricked us.'' Workers are demanding salary increases totaling $ 2.6 million annually. The average Honduran hospital worker earns about $ 200 a month. The health minister said the government can only give the workers annual total increases of $ 1.5 million `` because of the grave economic crisis facing <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>.'' He said the medical workers have declared some 36 strikes in the past two years to demand what he called `` exaggerated'' salary increases.
