<HEAD>Strike Paralyzes Eastern Operations at Atlanta</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AX4, AX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' jets sat idle in the fog at the nation's second-busiest airfield Saturday _ but not because of the weather. Striking mechanics virtually paralyzed <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> here, and normally bustling concourses were vacant except for pickets and clusters of frustrated fliers. Many would-be passengers were trying to get to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> for connections to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, where they had paid reservations on cruise ships. Others were students heading for warmer climes over spring break. Eastern, which handles about a third of the traffic through <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, originally had 278 departures scheduled for Saturday. By noon, only two planes had left, both for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. One Eastern flight had arrived. Planes from other airlines roared on and off the runways, past row on row of Eastern jets sitting idle. Airport spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> said the effect of the heavy fog, which could have backed up departing flights, was lessened because of the canceled <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flights. But that was no comfort to the passengers holding Eastern tickets. In the terminal, some played cards to pass the time while others snoozed, using carry-on luggage for pillows. Many complained they were n't told of flight cancellations until the last minute. `` I was on the phone with Eastern every day since Monday, and they kept telling me, ` It's going to fly, it's going to fly,''' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Tunner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, who was scheduled to meet a cruise ship in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> with his wife, <PERSON> Grace </PERSON>, and had made his reservations two months ago. `` We were on the phone three hours yesterday trying to get through to them and when we did, they told us at 4:30 -LRB- p.m. -RRB- that maybe it wo n't,'' he said. A frantic scramble ensued to get other tickets as far as <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Later Saturday morning, the Tunners managed to get on one of the two Eastern planes leaving for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, and were hoping they'd make it to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tunner </PERSON> said he was sorry for those on strike. `` But if we miss the ship, who's going to repay the $ 3,000 we paid for the cruise?'' he asked. It was suspenseful for the Tunners and the relatively few other travelers who managed to get on an Eastern plane. Strikebreakers loaded luggage onto a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 for Flight 843, bound for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, while <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> waited to see if a crew would report. Waiting passengers applauded when one pilot arrived. Later, the luggage was taken off and put on a smaller DC-9, which requires a smaller crew. The flight finally left for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> at 11:15 a.m., an hour and 45 minutes late, leaving many passengers behind. `` See you on the ship,'' one couple called to less-fortunate friends who did n't get on board. `` I hope you're right,'' came the reply. A second flight for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> left a few minutes later with those who did n't get on board the first plane, but airport officials said they did not know if Eastern would be able to get more planes out after that. Machinists and pilots picketed outside the terminal and in concourses where Eastern has flights. Nails were spread in an Eastern employee parking lot overnight, <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> said, but he said they were swept up and there was no damage. And most Eastern travelers were not going anywhere. `` Eastern was invisible,'' complained <PERSON> Kris </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiessel </PERSON>, a college student from <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, who was on her way to <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> with a friend. `` We called and they said everything was normal,'' she said. After the strike canceled her flight, she and her friend were able to use their Eastern tickets to get as far as <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> on a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> flight. `` When we got here they said they could send us back home.''
