<HEAD>Labor, Management Conflict Was Ready To Explode</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Labor-management tensions that erupted into a strike Saturday have been building inexorably for years at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, and both sides are dug in for what could be a fight to the end _ not just to their conflict, but to the 60-year-old airline itself. `` It's a tremendously unfortunate set of circumstances that has been developing for a while,'' said an emotional <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON>, an Eastern company spokesman and lobbyist for 22 years. `` At some point, we had to come to this.'' Management says the company, losing more than $ 1 million a day, just ca n't make it with its high-priced, demanding labor unions. The workers deny that they're overpaid and say management is tearing the company apart anyway, so they might as well stand and fight. `` Our people have been frustrated, they've been provoked, they've been brutalized They're ready for something forceful to show their feelings,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union District 100 president who joined the company as a mechanic in 1956, said before what he predicted would be `` a wingding of a strike.'' After a 17-month contract dispute, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest union walked out at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday and was quickly joined by pilots and flight attendants. With the carrier virtually shut down, company officials admitted they were surprised by the solidarity of the pilots with the Machinists. `` I think this has been building and everybody understands the company wants to divide the pilots and the -LRB- Machinists -RRB-,'' Eastern pilots union spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` It's not a Machinists issue. It's a <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> issue.'' Bankrupting the airline `` is a very real possibility,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` But that's where the airline is headed anyway, so we can face the music now when we have some leverage, or we can face the music later when there's nothing left.'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> chairman who bought Eastern three years ago, has solidified his anti-union reputation at a carrier that already had some of the airline industry's most recalcitrant unions. His new management in 1987 demanded 30 percent wage concessions it said was necessary to keep <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, bought on the brink of bankruptcy with nearly $ 2.5 billion in debts, alive. The balking unions were hit with thousands of layoffs, firings and suspensions. A flight attendant was fired after allegedly pocketing $ 2 in drink money, her union said, and another was disciplined for repeated absences after she was raped. Machinists' horror stories included a firing for refusing to work overtime on Christmas, while the pilots said their ranks shrank by more than 1,000 because of stress and forced overflying. The management said it was time for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workers to face reality _ they were being paid too much and were used to lax rules that were puttin Eastern out of business. The company, led for more than two decades by World War I flying ace <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rickenbacker </PERSON> and then for a decade by Apollo 8 astronaut <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Borman </PERSON>, was slow to react to the jet age and slower still to adjust to airline deregulation. <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> tried a number of innovative programs and at times seemed a model of enlightened management in his dealings with Eastern unions. But, labor leaders said, he could n't keep his promises and workers decided that wage givebacks they made in return for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> stock and profits were going down the drain. `` Eastern has been a cash-flow generator for its lenders for years, and has never been designed to make a profit,'' said Cole, an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilot for 19 years and the son of a pilot who flew with the airline for 38 years. <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said the company in happier times was excessively generous to unions that only became more militant. A major turning point came with the 1980 election of <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> to head the Machinists, he said. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, depicted by management as an ego-driven man with a near-mad vision of running the airline himself, believes giving employees company decision-making power improves productivity and service. He also says the workers have more pride in Eastern than management does. He has tried to organize an employee takeover of the company or attract `` white knights'' to buy out <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>. He and the other unions have fought <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> at every turn, with myriad lawsuits, grievances and lobbying in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But, <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said recently, the actions turned out to be only a delay of the inevitable showdown as, he claimed, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> tried to break the unions while `` cannibalizing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and leaving only a shell.'' <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> made <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s computer reservations system a subsidiary, reaped hundreds of millions of dollars in management fees and loans from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, and sold its profitable northeast Shuttle service to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, a sale that is awaiting final federal approval. While <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> was able to elicit some concessions, the unions looked at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s record and refused to give in to <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>. He beat a strike at tiny <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> International two decades ago and then ended a labor rebellion after his bitter takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> by sending the carrier into bankruptcy reorganization in 1983. Labor contracts were abrogated. `` No one believes <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> will stop trying to ruin the unions if we do n't fight,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, flight attendants union president. `` At <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, they have continued to ask employees to make concessions to fund mismanagement. It worked once, it worked twice, it ca n't continue to work any longer.'' `` This is really make it or break it,'' she said.
