<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Palacias </PERSON> did n't have to walk the Machinists picket lines that went up Saturday outside <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. He no longer works there. `` But I felt I could n't turn my back,'' said <PERSON> Palacias </PERSON>, 62, who retired in December 1987 after 22 years as a <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union aircraft mechanic. `` This is a showdown. I truly believe we have right on our side. It may just be a showdown to the death.'' Faced with a foe already accused of breaking one unionized airline, many in the 8,500-member <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union vow never to swap their red strike shirts for white surrender flags in the fight over wages and work conditions. Their fervor is not directed at the company, where many union members have worked since the last strike in 1966, but on its boss, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, who acquired Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. Three years earlier, he forced <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy reorganization in 1983 to end a labor confrontation and abrogate collective bargaining pacts. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> DeMaria </PERSON>, chief steward of the Machinists local in <LOCATION> Bayonne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said while walking the picket line Saturday: `` The labor of this country is aware of what a terrorist <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is. They consider the dispute not only against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> but a dispute for all labor.'' `` It's a war,'' said <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> baggage handler <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON>. `` There are a lot of people here ready to pa