 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s reputation as one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s toughest bosses is being tested with the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strike, but so is his image as a successful airline builder Since Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and its chairman took over <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> when it was on the brink of bankruptcy three years ago, the view of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> as the model for taking advantage of airline deregulation has been shaken. For all its cost-cutting, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> has been posting record losses. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> warned <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s workers last week that their company ca n't survive a strike by Machinists with the pilots and flight attendants joining in. The unions are gambling that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> ca n't survive, either, and that <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> will either yield or sell <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> to protect his parent corporation They concede the possibility, though, that he may finish stripping away <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> assets and leave a shell, or take the company into bankruptcy. The workers' willingness to fight Lorenzo even at risk to their future underlines his unpopular management style. Although he bought Eastern in February 1986 with the slogan `` we are n't union-busters; we're airline-builders,'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> added: `` There ai n't no <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>.'' The man recently called one of the nation's `` toughest bosses'' and a corporate `` loose cannon'' rolling on deck by `` Fortune'' magazine was born <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> 48 years ago to <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> immigrants in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, three miles from <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. At one point young <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> drove a truck and belonged to the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, whose schoolboy nickname of `` Frankie Smooth Talk'' was unearthed by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> labor leaders who also sport `` Stop Lorenzo'' buttons, graduated from <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, worked at <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern, then in 1971 helped buy money-losing <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, which became <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> in 1980. With an inner circle of ambitious, hard-driving executives well-versed in the ways of Wall Street and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has built Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> with a takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and its swallowing of such carriers as <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Frontier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and other small carriers. Continental has been predominantly nonunion since he got labor contracts abrogated in 1983 bankruptcy reorganization. He had mounted unsuccessful efforts to take o