<HEAD>PLO Official Quoted as Saying US Dialogue Should be Upgraded</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Stands for Jerusalem-dated story on news advisory.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A newspaper Saturday quoted a <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> spokesman as saying informal talks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are `` beating around the bush'' and that `` serious'' dialogue focusing on an international peace conference should begin. The comments by <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Abd-Rabboo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s information department chief, were reported by the <ORGANIZATION> Al-Anbaa </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. <PERSON> Abd-Rabboo </PERSON> was quoted as saying the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> `` notified <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> a week ago that it was time to resume a serious and in depth dialogue to prepare for an international conference.'' `` Dragging on with informal contacts that have been taking place in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> is beating round the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> and will not help bring about a settlement,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying. <PERSON> Abd-Rabboo </PERSON> could not be reached directly for comment, according to an aide in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, who demanded anonymity. There was no immediate reaction from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. It did not return telephone calls from The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The newspaper article was picked up by <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON>, whose report was then repeated on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s state-run radio and television Saturday. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> media reported that <PERSON> Abd-Rabboo </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> was not willing to continue the dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> under current conditions. But such comments did not appear in the <ORGANIZATION>