 local residents battled the fire Friday with helicopters, tractors and sprinkler systems, <PERSON> Borges </PERSON> said. But their efforts have been hampered by dry weather. In addition, the Indians resisted the intrusion of firefighters on their land. `` We're trying to isolate the fires, which are buring in four different areas of the forest right now,'' said <PERSON> Borges </PERSON>. `` But under these circumstances, it has n't been easy.'' Just 3 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, which once covered about 170,000 square miles along a 3,000-mile coastal strip, remains standing today. Some of the forest's rare monkeys, birds and trees, many found nowhere else in the world, face extinction. One of the trees near extinction is the Pau-Brasil, which gave the country its name.
