<TEXT>
 Here is a city-by-city wrapup of the effects of the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strike at key airports and transit systems. In general, almost all Eastern flights were canceled Saturday, despite the airlines' contingency plan to run a skeleton schedule; effects on other airlines and mass transit were negligible. MIAMI: Pickets at airport, nearby Eastern corporate headquarters and reservations system center of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent. No violence reported. As of midafternoon, seven flights had left the airport; normal daily schedule calls for 109 departures. No reported problems at other airlines or local transit services. <LOCATION> ORLANDO </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>: Some 140 pickets were working in shifts at about half-a-dozen locations. No flights departed; on a normal day 31 flights scheduled. No reports of violence or problems at other airlines. <LOCATION> ATLANTA </LOCATION>: Machinists and uniformed pilots picketed outside terminal and in Eastern concourses. Eastern had scheduled 278 departures for Saturday; only a few left. Nails were scattered in an Eastern parking lot but no violence or traffic delays reported. BALTIMORE-Baltimore-Washington International: Four Machinists pickets _ the maximum allowed by the airport. No violence or work slowdowns at other airlines reported. All 10 departures canceled. <LOCATION> NEWARK </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>: About 80 strikers on picket lines. Machinists joined by pilots and flight attendants. All flights canceled. Extra police assigned but no problems reported. NJ Transit officials ask a federal judge to issue injunction to head off threatened secondary strike Monday. NEW YORK-La Guardia: More than 120 Eastern machinists and other unions' pilots and flight attendants walk picket lines. All but one flight can