<HEAD>Disillusioned Communists Quitting Party, Pravda Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some Communist Party members are resigning because they do n't want to be associated with former leaders <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, Pravda said Saturday in an article urging Communists to face up to their painful past. For decades, the Soviet government hid sordid chapters of its history and even glorified <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> during his lifetime. But under President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or openness, the national press has been full of reports on repression and death under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and corruption under <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. Many older communists have reacted with shock and dismay at the denigration of their heroes. Pravda, the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, specifically cited electrician <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapayev </PERSON> and <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapodoinikov </PERSON>, a teacher, both from the <LOCATION> Gorno-Altai </LOCATION> region in western <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, as members who had dropped out because they were disillusioned. It said others have done the same but gave no figures. `` All my life appears to be worthless,'' <PERSON> Chapayev </PERSON>, who was a party member for 19 years before quitting recently, was quoted as saying. `` All my life I believed, and now all is gone to ashes, and not a blessed thing remains. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, Molotov, <PERSON> Voroshilov </PERSON> ... we were singing songs about them. We believed in them more than we believed in ourselves,'' he said. <PERSON> Vyacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Molotov </PERSON>, foreign minister during the prewar pact with <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Kliment </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Voroshilov </PERSON> were two of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s closest aides during the years when the Stalinist secret police killed millions of Soviet citizens Pravda quoted <PERSON> Zapodoinikov </PERSON> as saying, `` I can not remain a member of the party which had <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kunayev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nasriddinova </PERSON> and other scum in its ranks.'' <PERSON> Dinmukhamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunayev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vadgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nasriddinova </PERSON> are former regional party officials named in corruption scandals. Pravda correspondent <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomenko </PERSON> said the two disaffected party members from <PERSON> Gorno-Altai </PERSON> were not isolated cases but part of a larger problem dating back years. He said he remembered <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> party members quitting during <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s time, saying: `` It's because we can not live anymore in lies and hypocrisy.'' The newspaper said that although some might argue that the shameful portions of the party's history should be kept quiet, true party members should be able to stand up and face the truth. Admitting the truth, Pravda concluded, is painful but necessary. `` This is a pain similar to that which occurs when light strikes the eyes of a man who has long been in darkness and finally emerges into the sun, or when a doctor restores sight to a blind man, and takes from his eyes the black blindfold. Thus goes the revelation,'' the newspaper said.
