<HEAD>Jackson Calls on Evans, Sawyer to Unite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> began a three-day fast Saturday to urge Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and mayoral candidate <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> to unite and preserve the coalition formed by former Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> died and our ship wrecked,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told a rally at the headquarters of Operation PUSH, the civil rights group he founded. `` Rather than pick up the pieces, we chose to bomb the ship,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` Now we must build a new ship in five weeks.'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a black Democratic alderman running as an independent, refused to endorse <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> in last Tuesday's Democratic mayoral primary, which was won by <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> endorsed <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who is also black, in the primary and now supports <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> has so far declined to endorse <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> for the general election April 4. `` Division is our problem; unity and coalition are our solution,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` An Evans-Sawyer summit is essential.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the city's first black mayor, died in November 1987. The election this spring is to fill the remaining two years of his second term. After <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s death, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, a former alderman, was selected acting mayor by the City Council. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who is white, is the son of the late Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who ruled <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for 21 years. Former <PERSON> A