<HEAD>Tagged Sea Lion Returns To Feed On Ship-Locks Fish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sea lion relocated to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> in a campaign to stop the mammals from feasting on local fish returned to its hunting grounds here after traveling nearly 300 miles, a wildlife official said Saturday. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> sea lion spotted near the <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> ship locks Friday afternoon was the first relocated animal to return. `` He obviously likes it here,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION>. `` He knows a good life when he finds one.'' The sea lions wait by the locks and pick off steelhead, a seagoing trout, and salmon that are en route to their spawning grounds. Officials have trapped 18 <ORGANIZATION> sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> lions </ORGANIZATION> so far using a floating cage. Two died after being sedated for tagging and five more were released at the locks because of cold weather. To return, the sea lion had to swim about 150 miles up the coast, turn right, swim another 100 miles through the Strait of <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fuca </LOCATION>, turn right again and paddle the remaining 35 miles to the locks. Trapping will probably resume Monday, and officials are confident they can catch the remaining 13 or so animals, including the one who returned, for relocation to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said.
