<HEAD>European Rocket Launch Scrubbed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 29th launch of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s Ariane rocket was canceled three hours before lift-off Saturday night after two cables were accidentally disconnected, officials said. The cables were pulled loose when the support tower was being removed from the side of the launcher, said <PERSON> Frederic </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Allest </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Arianespace </ORGANIZATION>, which commercializes the rocket. It was not immediately clear whether the rocket could be launched on Sunday night. It was the second launch postponement for the Ariane 4 rocket, which was originally scheduled for lift-off on Tuesday but was delayed by a strike at the launch base here. The cables that were accidentally detached served to ventilate the MOP-1 European weather satellite, one of two payloads, and purge oxygen reservoirs.
