<TEXT>
 Guerrillas and government officials from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> on Saturday resumed peace talks interrupted by the shooting death of a leftist leader at <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s airport. The talks were the third between the two sides this year in search of a way to end a quarter-century of political violence in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, leader of the delegation from the rebels' April 19 Movement, told reporters before entering the talks that rebels had `` a concrete proposal'' to present to the government He did not say what the proposal contained but described it as `` what we think has to be done on an emergency basis to strengthen and broaden this process to respond to death with life, to darkness with hope and to war with peace.'' Before Friday's session <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said the talks were intended to set the stage for a peace agreement in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruedo </PERSON>, the government's representative, said the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> government continued to support the talks as a move toward peace. `` It is a process that can be difficult but is a light of hope for <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> at this time,'' he said. `` The road that must be followed is the road to democracy. The majority of Colombians believe that democracy is the solution,'' he said. Before entering the session at a luxury hotel, representatives of both sides condemned the killing Friday of <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Antequera </PERSON>, an executive board member of the Marxist-oriented <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, and another man and the wounding of eight others at <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Antequera </PERSON>, whose party was formed by th