<HEAD>Virginia Teacher Charged With Desecrating Flag in Banner Brouhaha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A schoolteacher in town for a seminar became entangled in a controversy over the use of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag in an art exhibit Saturday when she was arrested for walking on the Stars and Stripes. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Willhofft </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, was charged with desecrating the flag, a felony, in the first such arrest resulting from the exhibit at the School of the Art Institute of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The arrest came as two dozen critics of the exhibit picketed the art school and a state senator picked the flag up, removing it from the work, for the second day in a row. <PERSON> Willhofft </PERSON>'s attorney acknowledged that she stepped on the flag, but said she had no criminal or political motive. Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said the charge constituted `` harassment'' by the man who filed the complaint, <PERSON> Homer </PERSON> <PERSON> Choate </PERSON>, 47, of suburban <LOCATION> Lockport </LOCATION>, who opposes the work. `` And I would think the state's attorney's office would have something better to do than prosecute an innocent tourist,'' <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> added. At issue is a work by art student <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> titled `` What is the Proper Way to Display a <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Flag?'' which is part of a minority students' exhibit. The work features a montage of photographs depicting flag-draped coffins and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> burning the American flag, plus a book that invites viewer comments. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag is positioned on the floor in front of the book in such a way that viewers are likely to step on the flag to write in the book. The exhibit was closed to the public last weekend after veterans groups complained it was illegal and disrespectful to the flag and sued to try to force the school to remove it from the floor. Following a circuit judge's ruling Thursday, the show reopened. On Friday, state Sen. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudycz </PERSON> was detained briefly by officers after he picked the flag up from the floor. He did it again on Saturday, and asked the <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney's office to decide whether the exhibit violates laws against desecrating the flag The flag was put back in the exhibit. <PERSON> Willhofft </PERSON>, who teaches grades 6-8, was attending a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION>, said another of her attorneys, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaner </PERSON>. `` She had a free day, she was going to have lunch, she was going to shop at <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Schaner </PERSON> said. `` She had no intention of making a political protest. She just went to see the famous Art Institute of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` She stepped on the flag,'' he said. `` She wanted to see what was in the book.''
