Highway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> 29 </LOCATION> to head off trouble. The scene was tense, as demonstrators leaned over barbed-wire fences, screaming at a handful of skinheads watching them from atop a nearby hill. At one point, about six skinheads who tried to get into the rally got caught between police lines and protesters yelling insults. The white power rally was held on land owned by Dr. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON> of nearby <LOCATION> Vallejo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON> fled <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1937 with his Jewish family when he was 4 years old, family friend <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Coon </PERSON> told The Sacramento Bee. <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON>, a prominent 55-year-old specialist, had been told the gathering was to be an environmental rally but did not back out when he learned its true nature because he feared reprisals, said <PERSON> Coon </PERSON>, acting as <PERSON> Lonsdale </PERSON>'s spokesman. `` Would you like your house pushed over the hill? That's why he has n't spoken out against them,'' said <PERSON> Coon </PERSON>. `` He was told by the group that if he canceled out of this lease, they'd sue ... him, they'd ruin his practice,'' <PERSON> Coon </PERSON> added.
