<HEAD>Investing In S&amp;L Bailout Should Be A Good Bet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors soon may be offered the chance to buy into the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's savings and loan bailout plan, but will the $ 50 billion in bonds proposed to fund the program be a wise investment? `` It's a fairly secure security,'' said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. Stone, a senior economist at <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. She said she thinks the bonds will be attractive to investors But <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lakefield </PERSON>, an executive vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was more skeptical. `` I do n't think enough information is out in the marketplace at the present time to get a good feel,'' he said last week. `` We have n't gone through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. We're just speculating on the way it was presented along the way.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan envisions another new government agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> REFCO </ORGANIZATION>, to be set up to float the $ 50 billion in 30-year bonds over three years. Proceeds from the securities would be added to other government monies to rescue or close ailing thrifts, which make up about a third of the nation's 3,100 S & amp; Ls The principal on the bonds would be repaid through increased insurance premiums paid by the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L industry. Most of the interest payments on the bonds are expected to come from taxpayer money. It's expected that <ORGANIZATION> REFCO </ORGANIZATION> would buy zero-coupon <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds in the open market to collateralize the $ 50 billion debt. Analysts said there's no doubt the <ORGANIZATION> REFCO </ORGANIZATION> bonds will be safe but how attractive their yields will be remains to be seen. `` They're intangibles that are very difficult to quantify at this point,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brachfeld </PERSON>, an executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last month that he expeced the REFCO bonds to be traded at a premium of about a quarter of a percentage point over 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, which are now yielding around 9.15 percent But <PERSON> Lakefield </PERSON> said he expected the premium to be slightly higher, as is the case with other agency bonds. He noted that a bond the government issues to back military loans to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is about a third of a percentage point over comparable Treasuries. Government agencies have been issuing bonds over the years to finance anything from farm loans to home mortgages. Although they're backed by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, they are not considered direct obligations, and that's why their yields are slightly higher than Treasuries Ms. <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> REFCO </ORGANIZATION> bonds would appeal to `` almost anybody who is interested in a long-term investment,'' such as retirees, pension funds and life insurance companies <PERSON> Lakefield </PERSON> predicted the market would easily absorb them despite the large volume. `` The marketplace is a big, international marketplace,'' he said. Under <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan, $ 10 billion of the bonds would be sold in fiscal 1989, $ 25 billion in fiscal 1990 and $ 15 billion in fiscal 1991.
</TEXT>
