<SECOND>BC-Gibraltar S&amp;L,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Thrift Enters Regulatory Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's 10 biggest savings and loan companies, revealed Friday it had agreed with federal regulators to restrict its activities in hopes of stemming continued losses. The company also said it would require a substantial investment from outside or a merger to maintain federally required capital levels. The company, parent of the 86-branch <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Loan, with assets of $ 15 billion, has been losing money since late 1987, and recently disclosed it expected 1988 losses to reach $ 71 million to $ 76 million. Additionally, profit in the first quarter of 1989 will be cut by a $ 20 million writeoff from the closing of <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> MoneyCenter, which makes loans out of state, the company said in a news release. That closure is part of the supervisory agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the company said. The supervisory agreement had been expected since January, when the company revealed that federal regulators had declared <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> to be in `` unsafe and unsound'' condition. That finding was made despite the fact <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> met federal capital requirements, which govern how much cash the company must have available to back its loans. The agreement with regulators restricts <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> to making home loans in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, the company said. A previous agreement to restrict growth remains in effect. `` It is evident we will be unable to maintain required capital levels without a merger with or major investment by a third party,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thayer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> chairman, president and chief executive officer, said in a news release. `` Any such transaction will require significant <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> assistance ... There is no assurance that we will be successful in these efforts.'' <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> started on its slide with losses on real estate loans. Recently, it has been hurt by rising interest rates, which force it to pay more to attract deposits than it earns in interest on fixed-rate loans it made in the past.
</TEXT>
