<FIRST>d f PM-EconomyRdp     03-04 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Index Posts Second Straight Sharp Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government released more data pointing to continued strength in the economy, with reports that its key economic forecasting gauge rose sharply in January and that factory orders were strong that month except for a fallback in transportation equipment. But neither report, released on Friday, had a major effect on the financial markets. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.58 to 2,274.29. Bond prices were narrowly mixed, while the dollar declined against most major currencies. Meanwhile, the nation's Big Three automakers reported Friday that car and truck sales fell 17.9 percent in February compared with the same period last year. U.S.-made cars sold by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> sold at an average daily rate of 26,062 during the period this year. That compares with an average of 32,297 cars sold daily during the same period last year. Sales of light trucks averaged 15,561 a day in late February, compared with a daily rate of 18,419 during the same time last year. January's 0.6 percent rise in the <ORGANIZATION> Index </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indicators </ORGANIZATION> followed a 0.7 percent increase in December and provided fresh evidence that 1989 opened on a strong note despite widespread expectations of an impending slowdown. The index, designed to foretell economic activity six to nine months into the future, was up and down during much of last year. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said January's rise in the index `` shows a moderate level of growth which we believe is conducive to a healthy economy.'' However, analysts cautioned that the latest signs of robust economic activity could heighten concerns that the economy is speeding ahead too quickly to contain inflationary pressures. That, they said, could increase the risk of a recession by causing the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to act too aggressively as it pushes up interest rates to slow the economy and restrain inflation. `` I think there is a risk that we'll overreact to the data and push ourselves into a recession in the latter part of this year or in 1990,'' said economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagens </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a forecasting firm in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. A second report Friday from the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> offered additional evidence of strength in the economy Although orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods were down 1.3 percent in January, the decrease was attributed to a fallback in demand for transportation equipment from record levels set in December. Excluding transportation, factory orders were up 0.2 percent during January. And orders in the key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good barometer of industry investment plans, were up 1.6 percent in January.
</TEXT>
